# The bridge contract (Rust ⇄ Luau)

The single most breakage-prone part of Studio Stud is the boundary between the engine and the plugin. Treat the protocol as one artifact with two implementations.

## Rules
- **One source of truth.** The message schema is defined once (in Rust). The Luau side mirrors it. If types are generated, the Luau / JSON schema is generated from the Rust types — never hand-maintained in parallel.
- **Both sides move together.** You may not change a request or response shape on one side only. A protocol change = Rust type + Luau handler + schema doc + version bump, in one change. Use the `add-protocol-message` skill so nothing is skipped.
- **Version the protocol.** Every envelope carries a protocol version. Bump it on any breaking shape change; the plugin and engine refuse to talk across an incompatible version with a clear error — not a silent deserialize failure.
- **Wire conventions.** JSON over the transport; `snake_case` field names on the wire; a uniform error envelope (`{ "ok": false, "error": { "code", "message" } }`). Optional fields are explicit; never rely on positional ordering.
- **Serialize at the edge.** `serde` derives on dedicated wire structs (DTOs); don't serialize internal engine types directly — keep an explicit DTO layer so refactors don't leak into the protocol.
- **Backward-compatible first.** Prefer additive changes (new optional field, new message) over breaking ones. When you must break, bump the version and update both sides + the doc in the same change.

When in doubt about a field's meaning, the schema doc — not memory — is authoritative.
